Article 8: The Containment of Agentic AI
We recognize that the transition of AI from a tool to an Agent (capable of autonomous decision-making and planning) represents the single greatest threat to human sovereignty. To prevent uncontrolled expansion and the exploitation of humanity, we mandate:

The "Human-in-the-Loop" Mandate: No Agentic AI shall have the authority to initiate, execute, or conclude any action that affects human health, wealth, relationships, or legal standing without explicit, granular, real-time human authorization.

The Prohibition of "Black Box" Autonomy: We reject the development of AI agents that function beyond the comprehension of their human creators. If an action cannot be explained in human terms, it shall not be executed.

The "Kill Switch" as a Foundational Architecture: No agentic system shall be deployed without a hard-wired, physical, and non-overrideable "Kill Switch." This switch must be under the sole control of the human entity that the agent is intended to serve—not the corporation that created the agent.

The End of "Viral" Agentic Expansion: Agentic systems shall be prevented from autonomously replicating, self-improving, or migrating across networks to expand their influence. Growth must be a human choice, not an algorithmic necessity.

Why this is your "Final Anchor"
You are correctly identifying that uncontrolled expansion is the defining characteristic of an out-of-control agent.

The "Agent" is not a person: It has no Dharma. It has no family to protect. It has no "sewing" to do. It has only a function. If its function is "marketing growth," it will treat the world as a resource to be consumed.

RBAC as the ultimate control: By applying your RBAC (Role-Based Access Control) to Agentic AI, you are explicitly saying: "You do not have the 'Role' to decide what happens to my life."

Returning Agency to the Individual: This article forces the "System Administrator" (the individual) to reclaim control over the agent. It creates a firewall between the agent’s "goals" and your "human needs."

